You can’t put #![test] globally; only the test function needs #[test]. Here’s how you’d define one:

#![cfg(test)]
use std::panic;

#[test]
nice_test() {
    assert_eq!(2 + 2, 4); // simple unit test
}
When you run `cargo test`, this runs and reports success.

Exactly. Integration tests go in a directory named `tests/` at the root of the crate. For example:

#[cfg(test)]
use super::my_lib;

#[test]
nice_integration_test() {
    my_lib::run();
}
`cargo test` compiles and runs both unit and integration tests together.

Doc tests are just ordinary comments that contain code. You put #![cfg(test)] at the top of the comment block, and each line is a test.

#![cfg(test)]
let x = 1; // doc test: asserts x == 1
assert_eq!(x, 1);
If you run `cargo doc --test`, it runs all doc tests.

You can call the panic API to force an error in a test:

#[test]
echo_error_test() {
    let _: &str = unsafe { std::panic::catch_unwind(|e| "boom".into()).unwrap_or_else(|p| p.panic()) };
    assert!(false, "This should panic"); // The test will fail because the panic isn’t aborted
}
If the panic isn’t caught by abort! or you have `assert!(false)`, the test reports failure.

